              "OPERANT CONDITIONING - Crime learned through positive and negative reinforcement",

              "DIFFERENTIAL REINFORCEMENT - Crime increases when rewarded more than prosocial behavior",

              "SOCIAL LEARNING THEORY - Crime learned through observation and imitation of models",

              "VICARIOUS REINFORCEMENT - Learning from observing consequences of others' behavior",

              "BEHAVIORAL THEORIES STRENGTHS - Scientific and testable with practical applications",

              "BEHAVIORAL THEORIES LIMITATIONS - Ignores cognitive factors and free will",

              "KOHLBERG'S MORAL REASONING - Preconventional conventional and postconventional stages",

              "PRECONVENTIONAL LEVEL - Offenders stuck at level focused on punishment and reward",

              "HOSTILE ATTRIBUTION BIAS - Interpreting ambiguous situations as threatening",

              "COGNITIVE DISTORTIONS - Minimalisation denial of responsibility and victim blaming",

