              "Principle: If P(n₀) is true AND P(k) ⇒ P(k+1) for all k ≥ n₀, then P(n) is true for all n ≥ n₀",
              "Domino analogy: Knock down first domino (base case), ensure each domino knocks down next (inductive step)",
              "Step 1 - Base case: Prove the statement is true for n = n₀ (usually n₀ = 1)",
              "Step 2 - Inductive hypothesis: Assume the statement is true for n = k (some arbitrary positive integer)",
              "Step 3 - Inductive step: Prove the statement is true for n = k + 1 using the assumption",
              "Step 4 - Conclusion: By mathematical induction, the statement is true for all n ≥ n₀",
              "Proving summation formulae: Show Σf(r) from r=1 to n equals a given expression",
              "Example: Prove 1 + 2 + 3 + ... + n = n(n+1)/2 by induction",
              "Base case for summation: Verify formula holds for n = 1",
              "Inductive step for summation: Add (k+1)th term to both sides of P(k) to get P(k+1)",
              "Proving divisibility results: Show that f(n) is divisible by d for all n ≥ n₀",
              "Example: Prove 7ⁿ - 1 is divisible by 6 for all n ≥ 1",
              "Divisibility technique: Show f(k+1) - f(k) is divisible by d, or express f(k+1) using f(k)",
              "Proving inequalities: Show a(n) < b(n) or a(n) ≤ b(n) for all n ≥ n₀",
              "Example: Prove 2ⁿ > n² for all n ≥ 5",
              "Inequality technique: In inductive step, use algebraic manipulation and the assumption P(k)",
              "Proving matrix statements: Show Aⁿ equals a given expression for all n ≥ 1",
              "Matrix induction: Base case A¹ = A, inductive step Aᵏ⁺¹ = Aᵏ × A",
              "Example: If A = [1 1; 0 1], prove Aⁿ = [1 n; 0 1] by induction",
              "Proving recurrence relations: Show formula for nth term satisfies the recurrence",
              "Example: If uₙ₊₁ = 2uₙ + 1 with u₁ = 1, prove uₙ = 2ⁿ - 1",
              "Proving sequence properties: Monotonicity (increasing/decreasing), boundedness",
              "Strong induction: Assume P(1), P(2), ..., P(k) all true to prove P(k+1)",
              "Strong induction use cases: When P(k+1) depends on multiple previous terms",
              "Example of strong induction: Fibonacci sequence, every integer > 1 has prime factorization",
              "Common mistakes: Not stating the inductive hypothesis clearly",
              "Common mistakes: Proving P(k+1) without using P(k) (circular reasoning)",
              "Common mistakes: Forgetting to verify base case (essential foundation)",
              "Common mistakes: Incorrect algebraic manipulation in inductive step",
              "Writing style: Use clear mathematical language - 'Assume true for n = k', 'We need to prove for n = k+1'",
              "Exam technique: Always write 'By mathematical induction' in conclusion",
              "Exam technique: Show all working in inductive step, don't skip algebraic steps",
